<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="49">
<taxonomicName authority="Cook, 1896" authorityName="Cook" authorityYear="1896" class="Diplopoda" family="Trichopolydesmidae" genus="Bactrodesmus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Bactrodesmus" order="Polydesmida" pageId="0" pageNumber="49" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Bactrodesmus Cook, 1896</taxonomicName>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="49" type="type-species">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="49">Type-species.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="49">
<taxonomicName class="Diplopoda" family="Fuhrmannodesmidae" genus="Bactrodesmus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Bactrodesmus claviger" order="Polydesmida" pageId="0" pageNumber="49" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="claviger">Bactrodesmus claviger</taxonomicName>
Cook, 1896, by subsequent monotypy; Liberia.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="49">
The genus was first proposed as a nomen nudum (
<bibRefCitation author="Cook, OF" journalOrPublisher="The American Naturalist, Entomology" pageId="43" pageNumber="92" pagination="413 - 420" title="A new diplopod fauna in Liberia." volume="30" year="1896 a">Cook 1896a</bibRefCitation>
), but then properly typified (
<bibRefCitation author="Cook, OF" journalOrPublisher="Proceedings of the Academy of Natural Sciences of Philadelphia" pageId="44" pageNumber="93" pagination="257 - 267" title="Summary of new Liberian Polydesmoidea." volume="1896" year="1896 b">Cook 1896b</bibRefCitation>
). The sole useful information contained in the original description of 
<taxonomicName genus="B." lsidName="B. claviger" pageId="0" pageNumber="49" rank="species" species="claviger">B. claviger</taxonomicName>
concerns its small size (7 mm long, 1 mm wide), typically micropolydesmid facies (small paraterga, large and clubbed tergal setae arranged in three transverse rows etc.), strongly enlarged gonocoxae that fully conceal the telopodites and, above all, male legs 2, especially their tibiae, greatly enlarged compared to others (
<bibRefCitation author="Cook, OF" journalOrPublisher="Proceedings of the Academy of Natural Sciences of Philadelphia" pageId="44" pageNumber="93" pagination="257 - 267" title="Summary of new Liberian Polydesmoidea." volume="1896" year="1896 b">Cook 1896b</bibRefCitation>
). No number of body segments has been given.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
